          "title": "The statue and the stone — descending glory, ascending kingdom",
          "body": "The statue's metals descend in value (gold → silver → bronze → iron → iron mixed with clay) but increase in crushing force. Imperial history is not a story of progress but of brutalization; each empire is more powerful but less glorious than the last. The feet of iron and clay picture a final form that combines tactical strength with structural incoherence — peoples that *will not adhere to one another* (2:43). And then a *stone cut out without hands* strikes the feet, and the whole statue becomes chaff blown away without a trace (2:35). The stone is not made by human civilization; it has divine origin (*without hands* — cf. Hebrews 9:11, 24; Mark 14:58). The stone becomes a mountain that fills the whole earth — the kingdom of God in its consummated, world-filling form."
